\begin_body

\begin_layout Standard
[Equilibrium] It is an equilibrium also of asset bands - where consumption
 leads to a certain place.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
[Why care about separation] We care about separation only because it's relevant
 how status consumption are structured - more competitions at the local
 levels means less immigration pressures and availability of goods.
 More globalisation would mean more development and perception of a wider
 entity.
 Whether these are important or not is of importance to how status consumption
 is viewed in the developing countries.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An obvious limitation of the excess approach is that it does not differentiate
 between an excess in food items from an excess in clothes.
 There is no difference - in terms of excess 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

 - between a rural overspending on a wedding ceremony and the urban spending
 on cable TV subscriptions while in an itemwise analysis these would be
 considered explicitly.
 We favour the excess approach as it solves two keys issues with the measurement
 errors.
 First is the lack of observed prices for clothing or entertainment in the
 survey data.
 We avoid using a unit price of clothing by observing expenditure on clothing
 at local levels (see Gibson et al[#GibsonKimQualityBog2019] for measurement
 errors with this approach) to measure elasticities excess, and limit ourselves
 to testing whether excesses are separated across levels of asset-ownership
 hierarchies or not.
 The second issue is the mixing of daily-diary and monthly diary - which
 we avoid by separating the needs from quality.
 Notice also that any fixed-effects in the excess budget are removed through
 econometric methods.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
[Happiness data] One thing that's reassuring with our measure of excess
 is that indicates those who are unsatisified have proportionately higher
 excess.
 Extremely unsatisifed person don't have high excess.
 Extremely satisfied consumers tend to have less excess.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
[Entertainment is not a need] The base level of need is subject to debate.
 One can argue that within an economy, for example, that transportation
 is a need in the urban area while it isn't in a rural area.
 This hardly poses an issue with the excess approach since an urban consumer
 who has the the same total expenditure 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 as a rural consumer,would have a less excess due to higher transportation
 expenditure.
 However, if other needs such as entertainment - which we consider as part
 of excess - are considered more necessary in the urban area than the rural
 area (thus resulting in different 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi$
\end_inset

) may be at odds with our view of excess.
 
\bar under
While it is true that an urban consumer having the same 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 as the rural consumer may “feel” that her entertainment needs are higher
 due to peer effects, it cannot be ascertained from the consumption data
 alone whether the consumers move to urban areas to achieve a higher status
 or that the residents of the urban areas feel more pressures which represent
 a higher entertainment need (we attempt to use subjective well-being data
 to derive some conclusions).
 
\bar default
Now if we had considered entertainment as (higher) part of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi$
\end_inset

, an urban consumer could balance the utility from 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 (the trait of being urban) with having less excess than the rural consumer
 (higher 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi$
\end_inset

 results in less excess for same expenditure 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

).
 By sticking to a definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi$
\end_inset

 as only costs associated with assets, we consider role of peer effects
 by letting the asset ownership proxy the environment of the two consumers.
 More particularly, since the urban areas are always richer on the whole
 than rural areas, price
\begin_inset Formula $P_{\nu}$
\end_inset

 are bound to be different from the urban and rural consumer ( a higher
 price would ceteris paribus result in a higher excess).
 To compare two consumer having the same 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, we must therefore also consider their 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 which determines 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi$
\end_inset

 and the 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{\nu}$
\end_inset

 relevant for the consumer (which is is dependent on the environment defined
 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{\rho}A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

).
 Let's assume that the cost of basic needs 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

 is the same for the two consumer and the differences in 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi_{urban}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi_{rural}$
\end_inset

are negligible.
 Now if 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{urban}<A_{rural}$
\end_inset

, the 
\begin_inset Formula $x-\Psi(A_{rural})-\delta<x-\Psi(A_{urban})-\delta$
\end_inset

 i.e.
 the excess budget of the urban consumer is higher and the rural consumer's
 relative position is higher than that of urban consumer (since the higher
 number of rich residents in the urban area).
 Separation is therefore ruled out - particularly if the rural consumer
 also faces a lower 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{\nu}(A)$
\end_inset

 than the urban consumer .
 Similarly, when 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{urban}>A_{rural}$
\end_inset

the excess budget of the rural consumer is higher (since 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi(A_{urban})>\Psi(A_{rural})\Rightarrow x-\Psi(A_{urban})-\delta<x-\Psi(A_{rural})-\delta$
\end_inset

) and the urban consumer may or may not have a higher relative position
 than the rural consumer.
 A separation condition is avoided only if the rural consumer has a lower
 cost 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{\nu}(A)$
\end_inset

 than the urban consumer.
 The lifestyle differences in the rural area and the urban area are thus
 represented with 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-band dependent excess prices 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{\nu}$
\end_inset

.
 Instead of saying that the need for entertainment is higher in the urban
 area, we argue only to that 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{\nu}$
\end_inset

 in the urban area could create a separation from the rural area.
 The shape of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi(A)$
\end_inset

 is inferred from the costs observed in the consumption diary as costs associate
d with assets whereas the notion of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-band which are associated with
\begin_inset Formula $P_{\nu}$
\end_inset

are observed by using 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{\rho}A$
\end_inset

 at relevant hierarchies.
\end_layout

