 we could dismiss a separation.
 Likewise, if
\begin_inset Formula $P_{\nu}(A+dA)<P_{\nu}(A)$
\end_inset

 , we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{x-\Psi(A)-\delta}{P_{\nu}(A+dA)}>\frac{x-\Psi(A)-\delta}{P_{\nu}(A)}$
\end_inset

 and a separation is necessitated which we would observe as a lack of substituti
on in data i.e.
 consumers increasing excess as they move to the higher band.
 Finally 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi$
\end_inset

 for certain 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-bands (e.g.
 with utilities that are only available within the 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-band) could also create separation conditions.
 Assuming that we have 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{\nu}(A)=P_{\nu}(A+\Delta A)$
\end_inset

 for successive bands, separation is ensured when 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi(A+dA)<\Psi(A)$
\end_inset

 - as 
\begin_inset Formula $u(\frac{x-\Psi(A)-\delta}{P_{\nu}(A)},A)=u(\frac{x-\Psi(A+dA)-\delta}{P_{\nu}(A+dA)},A+dA)$
\end_inset

 is ruled out (note that separation is also trivially implied when 
\begin_inset Formula $x<\Psi(A+dA)+\delta$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
[Econometric test for separation] What separation means in the data is simply
 the substitution of excesses between 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-bands.
 If there is no separation across identified bands 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $A'$
\end_inset

 , one would observe that for a significant number of consumers 
\begin_inset Formula $u(\nu,A)=u(\nu',A')$
\end_inset

 for the same 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 In the cost-function function this would correspond to the consumers in
 the bands 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $A'$
\end_inset

 paying the same outlay 
\begin_inset Formula $c(u,P_{\nu}(A))$
\end_inset

 as they face different prices in the respective 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-bands i.e.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{alignat*}{1}
c(u,P_{\nu}(A)) & =c(u,P_{\nu}(A'))
\end{alignat*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In a regression with excess budget ratio
\begin_inset Formula $w_{\nu}$
\end_inset

as the dependent variable, therefore, a lack of separation would amount
 to a weak significance of the difference 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta A$
\end_inset

 between the bands.
 Separation is more on the other hand when excess is strongly influenced
 by the difference in bands
