.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The sign of coefficients of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta A$
\end_inset

 also indicate how significant the condition of separation might be - a
 higher in a richer 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-band means more separation than less excess in a higher 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-band.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For whether local peer effects are more important to the consumer than the
 wider-level wealth differences or not, we compare the dependence of excesses
 on local asset-difference 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta A_{local}$
\end_inset

 vs national asset-differences 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta A_{nat}$
\end_inset

or not (respectively).
 If excesses depend weakly on 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta A_{local}$
\end_inset

 but strongly on 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta A_{nat}$
\end_inset

, this means that status consumption is limited to the local region and
 the region is relatively separated from other regions.

\bar under
 Thus local peer effects are more dominant than differences in wealth at
 wider levels when .
 
\bar default
This could happen either if the consumer  resides in a relatively rich region
 or a relatively poor region.
 On the other hand, if we find a weak significance on 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta A_{nat}$
\end_inset

 but a stronger dependence on 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta A_{local}$
\end_inset

, then local separation exists and the rich consumer may be competing at
 a wider (national) level.
 In it is possible that there is weak significance across both hierarchies
 (implying that excesses are not particularly separated at either levels)
 or that there is strong dependence across both hierarchies (the consumers
 have their excesses within the limits the position in the local hierarchies
 and are then also separated by regional wealth at the wider level).
\end_layout

